{"title_page": "Darrin Horn", "text_new": "{{short description|American college basketball coach}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2010}} \n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Darrin Horn\n| image = Darrin Horn.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| current_title = Head coach\n| current_team = [[Northern Kentucky Norse men's basketball|Northern Kentucky]]\n| current_conference = [[Horizon League]]\n| current_record = 23\u20139\n| contract = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1972|12|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = \n| player_years1 = 1991\u20131995\n| player_team1 = [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers basketball|Western Kentucky]]\n| player_positions = [[Guard (basketball)|Guard]]\n| coach_years1 = 1995\u20131997\n| coach_team1 = Western Kentucky (assistant)\n| coach_years2 = 1997\u20131999\n| coach_team2 = [[Morehead State Eagles men's basketball|Morehead State]] (assistant)\n| coach_years3 = 1999\u20132003\n| coach_team3 = [[Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball|Marquette]] (assistant)\n| coach_years4 = 2003\u20132008\n| coach_team4 = Western Kentucky\n| coach_years5 = 2008\u20132012\n| coach_team5 = [[South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball|South Carolina]]\n| coach_years6 = 2015\u20132019\n| coach_team6 = [[Texas Longhorns men's basketball|Texas]] (assistant)\n| coach_years7 = 2019\u2013Present\n| coach_team7 = [[Northern Kentucky Norse men's basketball|Northern Kentucky]] \n| overall_record = 194\u2013120\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = 2\u20131 ([[NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Division I]])<br />1\u20133 ([[National Invitation Tournament|NIT]])\n| championships = [[Sun Belt Conference|Sun Belt]] regular season (2006)<br />[[Sun Belt Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Sun Belt Tournament]] ([[2008 Sun Belt Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|2008]])<br />[[Horizon League Men's Basketball Tournament|Horizon League Tournament]] ([[2020 Horizon League Men's Basketball Tournament|2020]])\n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Darrin McKinley Horn''' (born December 24, 1972) is an American [[college basketball]] [[coach (sports)|head coach]] at [[Northern Kentucky Norse men's basketball|Northern Kentucky University]], having previously served as an assistant coach at the [[Texas Longhorns men's basketball|University of Texas]] and a head coach for the [[Division I (NCAA)]] programs at [[Western Kentucky University]] and at the [[University of South Carolina]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/news/story?id=3322582 |title=Western Kentucky coach Horn leaving for S. Carolina - Men's College Basketball - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=April 1, 2008 |accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in Kentucky, Horn played guard for the 1991 [[Kentucky High School Athletic Association|KHSAA]] state runner-up [[Tates Creek High School]] Commodores in [[Lexington, Kentucky]] for coach Nolan Barger.<ref>http://www.thestate.com/2008/04/06/367040/morris-darrin-horn-action-man.html{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn college, Horn played for [[Western Kentucky University]] [[WKU Hilltoppers basketball|Hilltoppers]] in [[Bowling Green, Kentucky]] from 1991 to 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://espn1420.com/jays-memorable-moment-5-toppers-topped/|title=Jay's Memorable Moment #5 \u2013 'Toppers Topped|first=Jay|last=Walker|website=SPORTS RADIO ESPN 1420}}</ref> He was a crowd favorite, hitting a game-winning three-pointer to defeat the [[University of Louisville]] on February 16, 1993, in [[Freedom Hall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hilltopperhaven.com/flashbacks/93ul.html |title=Hilltopper Flashbacks |publisher=Hilltopper Haven |date= |accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref>  While Horn played at WKU, the team made it to the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|NCAA Tournament]] three times, defeating [[Memphis State]] (led by [[Anfernee Hardaway]]) and [[Seton Hall]] in 1993 before losing to [[Florida State University]]; losing to the [[University of Texas]] in the first round in 1994; and defeating the [[University of Michigan]] before losing to the [[University of Kansas]] (led by [[Greg Ostertag]]) in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/tournament/history/_/team1/7903 |title=NCAA Basketball Tournament History: Western Kentucky Hilltoppers - ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref> Horn played for [[Ralph Willard]] and [[Matt Kilcullen]] while at WKU.\n\n==Coaching career==\n===Assistant coach===\nHorn served as an assistant coach from 1995 to 1997 at WKU for then-coach [[Matt Kilcullen]] before departing for [[Morehead State University]] to serve under [[Kyle Macy]] for two seasons before departing for Marquette.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allcoachnetwork.com/horn/bio.html|title=Darrin Horn -- Official Website -- South Carolina Basketball|website=www.allcoachnetwork.com}}</ref>\n\nHe was an assistant coach at [[Marquette University]] under [[Tom Crean (basketball coach)|Tom Crean]]. That Marquette team was led by future [[NBA]] players [[Dwyane Wade]] and [[Travis Diener]].<ref>http://www.gamecocksonline.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/082609aab.html</ref> Crean and Horn first crossed paths when Horn played at WKU and Crean was an assistant for the Hilltoppers under head coach [[Ralph Willard]].\n\n===Head coach===\nAfter his tenure at Marquette, Horn was hired as the head coach at [[Western Kentucky University]] to replace [[Dennis Felton]], who left for the [[University of Georgia]] after three trips to the NCAA Tournament. Prior to his hiring, [[Travis Diener]] recommended Horn to the then-WKU athletic director Wood Selig.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/15510-south-carolina-basketball-hires-darrin-horn|title=South Carolina Basketball Hires Darrin Horn|first=Tim|last=Pollock|website=Bleacher Report}}</ref>\n\nHorn compiled a record of 111\u201348 in five seasons at his [[alma mater]], WKU. He led the Hilltoppers to the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|Sweet 16]], the third round of the [[2008 NCAA Men's Basketball Tournament]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=284000038|title=Western Kentucky vs. UCLA - Box Score - March 27, 2008 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> a tournament run that included one of the most celebrated buzzer beaters in college basketball history, a [[three-pointer]] by Ty Rogers against [[Drake Bulldogs men's basketball|Drake]] in [[overtime]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wkusports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5400&ATCLID=204906189 |title=VOTE: Is Rogers' Buzzer-Beater the Best of All-Time? - Western Kentucky University Official Athletics Site |publisher=Wkusports.com |accessdate=April 30, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101102052509/http://www.wkusports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5400 |archivedate=November 2, 2010 }}</ref>  Their run ended with a 10-point loss to top-seeded [[UCLA Bruins men's basketball|UCLA]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=284000038|title=Western Kentucky vs. UCLA - Game Recap - March 27, 2008 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2008, Horn was hired as the new men's coach at the [[University of South Carolina]], replacing [[Dave Odom]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\nOn March 13, 2012, he was fired as head coach of the [[South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball|Gamecocks]] after going 60-63 in 4 seasons with only one postseason appearance.<ref>{{cite web|title=Darrin Horn fired by South Carolina|url=http://www.wrdw.com/sports/headlines/Darrin_Horn_fired_by_South_Carolina_142492705.html|publisher=WRDW-TV Augusta|accessdate=March 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2019 Horn was hired as head coach by [[Northern Kentucky Norse men's basketball|Northern Kentucky University]] replacing [[John Brannen (basketball)|John Brannen]] who left to take the [[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|University of Cincinnati]] job. <ref>{{cite web|title=Darrin Horn to replace John Brannen as NKU Norse head coach\n|url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/sports/2019/04/23/darrin-horn-new-northern-kentucky-basketball-coach/3555566002/|accessdate=April 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching style==\nHorn's teams are known for their up-tempo style of play, full-court trapping defense and conditioning.  While at WKU, Horn's teams averaged 47% field goal accuracy and averaged approximately 77 points per game.<ref>http://www.gamecocksonline.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/horn_darrin00.html</ref>\n\n===Former players in the NBA===\n*[[Mo Bamba]]\n*[[Jarrett Allen]]\n*[[Isaiah Taylor]]\n*[[Courtney Lee]]\n*[[Jeremy Evans]]\n*[[Dwyane Wade]]\n*[[Travis Diener]]\n*[[Steve Novak]]\n*[[Jaxson Hayes]]\n*[[Myles Turner]]\n\n==Personal life==\nHorn is married to Carla Walker Horn of [[Franklin, Tennessee]]. The couple have two children.\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start | type = | conference = | postseason = | poll = }}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name       = [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers basketball|Western Kentucky Hilltoppers]]\n | conference = [[Sun Belt Conference]]\n | startyear  = 2003\n | endyear    = 2008\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | season       = [[2003\u201304 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2003\u201304]]\n | name         = Western Kentucky\n | overall      = 15\u201313\n | conference   = 8\u20136\n | confstanding = 5th\n | postseason   = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | season       = [[2004\u201305 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2004\u201305]]\n | name         = Western Kentucky\n | overall      = 22\u20139\n | conference   = 9\u20135\n | confstanding = 2nd <small>(East)</small>\n | postseason   = [[2005 National Invitation Tournament|NIT First Round]]\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = conference\n | season       = [[2005\u201306 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2005\u201306]]\n | name         = Western Kentucky\n | overall      = 23\u20138\n | conference   = 12\u20132\n | confstanding = 1st <small>(East)</small>\n | postseason   = [[2006 National Invitation Tournament|NIT First Round]]\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | season       = [[2006\u201307 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2006\u201307]]\n | name         = Western Kentucky\n | overall      = 22\u201311\n | conference   = 12\u20136\n | confstanding = 2nd <small>(East)</small>\n | postseason   = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = conference tournament\n | season       = [[2007\u201308 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2007\u201308]]\n | name         = [[2007\u201308 WKU Hilltoppers basketball team|Western Kentucky]]\n | overall      = 29\u20137\n | conference   = 16\u20132\n | confstanding = T\u20131st <small>(East)</small>\n | postseason   = [[2008 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Division I Sweet 16]]\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Western Kentucky\n | overall    = 111\u201348 ({{Winning percentage|111|48}})\n | confrecord = 57\u201321 ({{Winning percentage|57|21}})\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name       = [[South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball|South Carolina Gamecocks]]\n | conference = [[Southeastern Conference]]\n | startyear  = 2008\n | endyear    = 2012\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = division\n | season       = [[2008\u201309 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2008\u201309]]\n | name         = [[2008\u201309 South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball team|South Carolina]]\n | overall      = 21\u201310\n | conference   = 10\u20136\n | confstanding = T-1st <small>(East)</small>\n | postseason   = [[2009 National Invitation Tournament|NIT First Round]]\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | season       = [[2009\u201310 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2009\u201310]]\n | name         = [[2009\u201310 South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball team|South Carolina]]\n | overall      = 15\u201316\n | conference   = 6\u201310\n | confstanding = 5th <small>(East)</small>\n | postseason   = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | season       = [[2010\u201311 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2010\u201311]]\n | name         = [[2010\u201311 South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball team|South Carolina]]\n | overall      = 14\u201316\n | conference   = 5\u201311\n | confstanding = 6th <small>(East)</small>\n | postseason   = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | season       = [[2011\u201312 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2011\u201312]]\n | name         = [[2011\u201312 South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball team|South Carolina]]\n | overall      = 10\u201321\n | conference   = 2\u201314\n | confstanding = 12th\n | postseason   = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = South Carolina\n | overall    = 60\u201363 ({{Winning percentage|60|63}})\n | confrecord = 23\u201341 ({{Winning percentage|23|41}})\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name       = [[Northern Kentucky Norse men's basketball|Northern Kentucky Norse]]\n | conference = [[Horizon League]]\n | startyear  = 2019\n | endyear    = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = conference tournament\n | season       = [[2019\u201320 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2019\u201320]]\n | name         = [[2019\u201320 Northern Kentucky Norse men's basketball team|Northern Kentucky]]\n | overall      = 23\u20139\n | conference   = 13\u20135\n | confstanding = 2nd\n | postseason   = [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Division I]]\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Northern Kentucky\n | overall    = 23\u20139 ({{Winning percentage|23|9}})\n | confrecord = 13\u20135 ({{Winning percentage|13|5}})\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record End\n | overall = 194\u2013120 ({{Winning percentage|194|120}})\n}}\nSource<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/coaches/h/hornda01.html Darrin Horn] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110305045208/http://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/coaches/h/hornda01.html |date=March 5, 2011 }}. sports-reference.com</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://texassports.com/staff.aspx?staff=248 Texas profile]\n* [http://www.gamecocksonline.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/horn_darrin00.html South Carolina profile]\n\n{{Horizon League men's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{WKU Hilltoppers basketball coach navbox}}\n{{South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{Northern Kentucky Norse men's basketball coach navbox}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Horn, Darrin}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball coaches from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:College basketball announcers in the United States]]\n[[Category:College men's basketball head coaches in the United States]]\n[[Category:Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Morehead State Eagles men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Northern Kentucky Norse men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Point guards]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lexington, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Tates Creek High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Texas Longhorns men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Western Kentucky Hilltoppers basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Western Kentucky Hilltoppers basketball players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college basketball coach}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2010}} \n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Darrin Horn\n| image = Darrin Horn.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| current_title = Head coach\n| current_team = [[Northern Kentucky Norse men's basketball|Northern Kentucky]]\n| current_conference = [[Horizon League]]\n| current_record = 23\u20139\n| contract = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1972|12|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = \n| player_years1 = 1991\u20131995\n| player_team1 = [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers basketball|Western Kentucky]]\n| player_positions = [[Guard (basketball)|Guard]]\n| coach_years1 = 1995\u20131997\n| coach_team1 = Western Kentucky (assistant)\n| coach_years2 = 1997\u20131999\n| coach_team2 = [[Morehead State Eagles men's basketball|Morehead State]] (assistant)\n| coach_years3 = 1999\u20132003\n| coach_team3 = [[Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball|Marquette]] (assistant)\n| coach_years4 = 2003\u20132008\n| coach_team4 = Western Kentucky\n| coach_years5 = 2008\u20132012\n| coach_team5 = [[South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball|South Carolina]]\n| coach_years6 = 2015\u20132019\n| coach_team6 = [[Texas Longhorns men's basketball|Texas]] (assistant)\n| coach_years7 = 2019\u2013Present\n| coach_team7 = [[Northern Kentucky Norse men's basketball|Northern Kentucky]] \n| overall_record = 194\u2013120\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = 2\u20131 ([[NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Division I]])<br />1\u20133 ([[National Invitation Tournament|NIT]])\n| championships = [[Sun Belt Conference|Sun Belt]] regular season (2006)<br />[[Sun Belt Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Sun Belt Tournament]] ([[2008 Sun Belt Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|2008]])<br />[[Horizon League Men's Basketball Tournament|Horizon League Tournament]] ([[2020 Horizon League Men's Basketball Tournament|2020]])\n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Darrin McKinley Horn''' (born December 24, 1972) is an American [[college basketball]] [[coach (sports)|head coach]] at [[Northern Kentucky Norse men's basketball|Northern Kentucky University]], having previously served as an assistant coach at the [[Texas Longhorns men's basketball|University of Texas]] and a head coach for the [[Division I (NCAA)]] programs at [[Western Kentucky University]] and at the [[University of South Carolina]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/news/story?id=3322582 |title=Western Kentucky coach Horn leaving for S. Carolina - Men's College Basketball - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=April 1, 2008 |accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in Kentucky, Horn played guard for the 1991 [[Kentucky High School Athletic Association|KHSAA]] state runner-up [[Tates Creek High School]] Commodores in [[Lexington, Kentucky]] for coach Nolan Barger.<ref>http://www.thestate.com/2008/04/06/367040/morris-darrin-horn-action-man.html{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn college, Horn played for [[Western Kentucky University]] [[WKU Hilltoppers basketball|Hilltoppers]] in [[Bowling Green, Kentucky]] from 1991 to 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://espn1420.com/jays-memorable-moment-5-toppers-topped/|title=Jay's Memorable Moment #5 \u2013 'Toppers Topped|first=Jay|last=Walker|website=SPORTS RADIO ESPN 1420}}</ref> He was a crowd favorite, hitting a game-winning three-pointer to defeat the [[University of Louisville]] on February 16, 1993, in [[Freedom Hall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hilltopperhaven.com/flashbacks/93ul.html |title=Hilltopper Flashbacks |publisher=Hilltopper Haven |date= |accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref>  While Horn played at WKU, the team made it to the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|NCAA Tournament]] three times, defeating [[Memphis State]] (led by [[Anfernee Hardaway]]) and [[Seton Hall]] in 1993 before losing to [[Florida State University]]; losing to the [[University of Texas]] in the first round in 1994; and defeating the [[University of Michigan]] before losing to the [[University of Kansas]] (led by [[Greg Ostertag]]) in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/tournament/history/_/team1/7903 |title=NCAA Basketball Tournament History: Western Kentucky Hilltoppers - ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref> Horn played for [[Ralph Willard]] and [[Matt Kilcullen]] while at WKU.\n\n==Coaching career==\n===Assistant coach===\nHorn served as an assistant coach from 1995 to 1997 at WKU for then-coach [[Matt Kilcullen]] before departing for [[Morehead State University]] to serve under [[Kyle Macy]] for two seasons before departing for Marquette.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allcoachnetwork.com/horn/bio.html|title=Darrin Horn -- Official Website -- South Carolina Basketball|website=www.allcoachnetwork.com}}</ref>\n\nHe was an assistant coach at [[Marquette University]] under [[Tom Crean (basketball coach)|Tom Crean]]. That Marquette team was led by future [[NBA]] players [[Dwyane Wade]] and [[Travis Diener]].<ref>http://www.gamecocksonline.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/082609aab.html</ref> Crean and Horn first crossed paths when Horn played at WKU and Crean was an assistant for the Hilltoppers under head coach [[Ralph Willard]].\n\n===Head coach===\nAfter his tenure at Marquette, Horn was hired as the head coach at [[Western Kentucky University]] to replace [[Dennis Felton]], who left for the [[University of Georgia]] after three trips to the NCAA Tournament. Prior to his hiring, [[Travis Diener]] recommended Horn to the then-WKU athletic director Wood Selig.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/15510-south-carolina-basketball-hires-darrin-horn|title=South Carolina Basketball Hires Darrin Horn|first=Tim|last=Pollock|website=Bleacher Report}}</ref>\n\nHorn compiled a record of 111\u201348 in five seasons at his [[alma mater]], WKU. He led the Hilltoppers to the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|Sweet 16]], the third round of the [[2008 NCAA Men's Basketball Tournament]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=284000038|title=Western Kentucky vs. UCLA - Box Score - March 27, 2008 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> a tournament run that included one of the most celebrated buzzer beaters in college basketball history, a [[three-pointer]] by Ty Rogers against [[Drake Bulldogs men's basketball|Drake]] in [[overtime]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wkusports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5400&ATCLID=204906189 |title=VOTE: Is Rogers' Buzzer-Beater the Best of All-Time? - Western Kentucky University Official Athletics Site |publisher=Wkusports.com |accessdate=April 30, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101102052509/http://www.wkusports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5400 |archivedate=November 2, 2010 }}</ref>  Their run ended with a 10-point loss to top-seeded [[UCLA Bruins men's basketball|UCLA]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=284000038|title=Western Kentucky vs. UCLA - Game Recap - March 27, 2008 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2008, Horn was hired as the new men's coach at the [[University of South Carolina]], replacing [[Dave Odom]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\nOn March 13, 2012, he was fired as head coach of the [[South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball|Gamecocks]] after going 60-63 in 4 seasons with only one postseason appearance.<ref>{{cite web|title=Darrin Horn fired by South Carolina|url=http://www.wrdw.com/sports/headlines/Darrin_Horn_fired_by_South_Carolina_142492705.html|publisher=WRDW-TV Augusta|accessdate=March 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2019 Horn was hired as head coach by [[Northern Kentucky Norse men's basketball|Northern Kentucky University]] replacing [[John Brannen (basketball)|John Brannen]] who left to take the [[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|University of Cincinnati]] job. <ref>{{cite web|title=Darrin Horn to replace John Brannen as NKU Norse head coach\n|url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/sports/2019/04/23/darrin-horn-new-northern-kentucky-basketball-coach/3555566002/|accessdate=April 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching style==\nHorn's teams are known for their up-tempo style of play, full-court trapping defense and conditioning.  While at WKU, Horn's teams averaged 47% field goal accuracy and averaged approximately 77 points per game.<ref>http://www.gamecocksonline.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/horn_darrin00.html</ref>\n\n===Former players in the NBA===\n*[[Mo Bamba]]\n*[[Jarrett Allen]]\n*[[Isaiah Taylor]]\n*[[Courtney Lee]]\n*[[Jeremy Evans]]\n*[[Dwyane Wade]]\n*[[Travis Diener]]\n*[[Steve Novak]]\n*[[Jaxson Hayes]]\n*[[Myles Turner]]\n\n==Personal life==\nHorn is married to Carla Walker Horn of [[Franklin, Tennessee]]. The couple have two children.\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start | type = | conference = | postseason = | poll = }}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name       = [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers basketball|Western Kentucky Hilltoppers]]\n | conference = [[Sun Belt Conference]]\n | startyear  = 2003\n | endyear    = 2008\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | season       = [[2003\u201304 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2003\u201304]]\n | name         = Western Kentucky\n | overall      = 15\u201313\n | conference   = 8\u20136\n | confstanding = 5th\n | postseason   = \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | season       = [[2004\u201305 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2004\u201305]]\n | name         = Western Kentucky\n | overall      = 22\u20139\n | conference   = 9\u20135\n | confstanding = 2nd <small>(East)</small>\n | postseason   = [[2005 National Invitation Tournament|NIT First Round]]\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = conference\n | season       = [[2005\u201306 NCAA Division I men's